issue.body:
In my IIS web site after a few minutes of work I am getting

```
2015-11-02T05:02:09 Caught exception System.ObjectDisposedException: Cannot access a disposed object.
Object name: 'The rolling file has been disposed.'.
   at Serilog.Sinks.RollingFile.RollingFileSink.Emit(LogEvent logEvent) in c:\projects\serilog\src\Serilog.FullNetFx\Sinks\RollingFile\RollingFileSink.cs:line 88
   at Serilog.Core.Sinks.SafeAggregateSink.Emit(LogEvent logEvent) in c:\projects\serilog\src\Serilog\Core\Sinks\SafeAggregateSink.cs:line 38 while emitting to sink Serilog.Sinks.RollingFile.RollingFileSink.
```

My logging configuration looks like

```
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Text;
using MRG.Fulfillment.Infrastructure.Logging.Seri;
using Serilog;
using Serilog.Debugging;
using Serilog.Events;
using Serilog.Formatting.Json;
using Serilog.Sinks.Elasticsearch;
using Serilog.Sinks.RollingFile;

namespace MRG.Fulfillment.Infrastructure.Logging
{
    public static class LoggingBootstrapper
    {
        public static LoggerConfiguration Configuration;

        public static void Bootstrap(LoggingConfig config)
        {
            Configuration = new LoggerConfiguration();

            if (config.LogToConsole)
            {
                //log to console
                Configuration.WriteTo.Console(
                    outputTemplate:
                        "{Timestamp:yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss} {RequestId} [{Level}] {Message}{NewLine}{Exception}",
                    restrictedToMinimumLevel: LogEventLevel.Information);
            }

            if (config.ElasticSearch != null)
            {
                //elastic search
                Configuration.WriteTo.Elasticsearch(new ElasticsearchSinkOptions(config.ElasticSearch)
                {
                    AutoRegisterTemplate = true,
                    BufferBaseFilename = config.ElasticSearchBuffer,
                    MinimumLogEventLevel = LogEventLevel.Verbose,
                });
            }

            if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(config.LogPath))
            {
                Configuration.
                    WriteTo.Sink(new RollingFileSink(config.LogPath, new JsonFormatter(), 2097152, 10, Encoding.UTF8));
            }

            if (config.Debug)
            {
                if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(config.DebugPath))
                {
                    SelfLog.Out = Console.Out;
                }
                else
                {
                    Directory.CreateDirectory(Path.GetDirectoryName(config.DebugPath));
                    var file = File.CreateText(config.DebugPath);
                    SelfLog.Out = TextWriter.Synchronized(file);
                }
            }

            Common.Logging.LogManager.Adapter = new SerilogFactoryAdapter(Configuration.CreateLogger());

            Configuration.CreateLogger().Information("BOOTING UP");

            AppDomain.CurrentDomain.UnhandledException +=
                (sender, args) =>
                {
                    Configuration.CreateLogger().Error(args.ExceptionObject as Exception, "GLOBAL ERROR");
                };
        }
    }
}
```

body:
Thanks for the heads-up @jeremymeng. Sounds like @IanYates has more background than I do here.

A few thoughts and obsevations though:

``` csharp
            var config = new LoggerConfiguration()
                .MinimumLevel.Debug()
                .WriteTo.TextWriter(output);

            var factory = new SerilogFactory(config);
```

Having `SerilogFactory` accept a `LoggerConfiguration` is a bit of a risky proposition. Things will go awry, for example, if the configuration includes something like `WriteTo.File()` where at most one configuration can use the specified file.

If instead, `SerilogFactory` accepted an `ILogger`, customised loggers for various contexts can be created from it:

``` csharp
var componentA = log.ForContext("Component", "A");
componentA.Information("Hello from A!");

// or

var componentB = log.ForContext(typeof(ComponentB));
```

There's an example Autofac integration for Serilog here that could provide some inspiration: https://github.com/nblumhardt/autofac-serilog-integration

Let me know if this makes sense or if I can provide more info.
